    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>This essentially involves the following tests: </b>"
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "list"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "items" : [
    
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Insulation resistance:</b>                      This test checks whether the insulation resistance is above the limit value defined in the standard. The insulation resistance is measured by connecting a 1000 volt DC test voltage to the live conductors to the housing. This should be                      <b>>2.5 MΩ</b>                      for the high-voltage battery.                 "
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Dielectric strength:</b>                      The dielectric strength test (DC) is used to check the electric insulation capacity and dielectric strength or compliance with the required air gaps and creepage distances in the high-voltage battery. The insulation between the cell floor and cooling plate is also checked.                      <b>The test is performed with a voltage of 2.1 kV for 1 sec. This test must only be performed by appropriately trained personnel in compliance with all safety regulations and in accordance with instructions for working on live systems!</b>"
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Potential equalisation:</b>                      This test is used to make sure that all components are connected to a ground reference in order to ensure that in the event of a fault, any fault current or leakage current that occurs is conducted away via the housing. If the electric connection is not OK, contact voltage on conductive parts of the high-voltage battery, particularly the housing, may be too high. It also ensures that any insulation faults that occur are reliably detected.                 "
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Absence of electric charge (test for possible residual voltage or charge):</b>                      The test for verifying absence of electric charge or residual voltage that can occur as a result of charging, for example, during repairs is used to protect the worker against possible electric shock from exposed parts or connections of the high-voltage battery.                 "
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Cooling system leak test:</b>                      The leak-tightness of the cooling plates and the connected coolant distributor must be checked before filling the cooling system with a water-glycol mixture. Any emerging coolant will cause insulation faults and can result in a short circuit in the high-voltage battery.                 "
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "<b>Battery housing leak test:</b>                      Before installing the HV battery in the vehicle, the battery housing must be checked to ensure that it is leak-tight. Penetrating moisture/liquid causes insulation faults and can result in a short circuit in the HV battery.                 "
    
    }
    
    }
    
    ]
    
    }
    
